article.description: DeLisha Milton-Jones scored 15 points against her former team, leading the visiting Washington Mystics to a 74-68 victory over the Los Angeles Sparks on Tuesday.
article.headline: Milton-Jones scores 15 vs. former team in win
article.linkText: Mystics prevail for the first time in Los Angeles
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- DeLisha Milton-Jones scored 15 points against
her former team, leading the Washington Mystics to a 74-68 victory
over the Los Angeles Sparks on Tuesday.

Chasity Melvin and Alana Beard added 14 points apiece, and
Melvin grabbed nine rebounds for the Mystics (10-10), who won in
Los Angeles for the first time in the franchise's eight-year
history.

"We didn't know that," said Milton-Jones, traded to Washington
for Chamique Holdsclaw in March. "It just makes the visit that
much sweeter when you can come into hostile territory knowing that
you were just traded and get a win."

Holdsclaw, averaging a league-leading 19.3 points, scored 17 for
the Sparks (10-9), who have lost three of their last four. Doneeka
Hodges added a career-high 16 points and tied a career best with
five assists.

Holdsclaw added six rebounds and five assists as she returned to
the lineup after missing one game because of a pulled left
hamstring.

Los Angeles used a 10-0 surge to take a 57-54 lead with 10:29 to
play. Then, with the score tied at 63, the Mystics made their move.
Melvin converted a layup and Charlotte Smith-Taylor made a
3-pointer to give Washington a 68-63 lead with 3:28 left.

Those points came while Sparks center Lisa Leslie was on the
bench after injuring a knee with 4:55 remaining. She returned with
1:32 left.

"We got a break because Leslie went out," Mystics coach Richie
Adubato said. "The time that she was out, we went to Chas [Melvin]
and she was able to take the ball to the hole twice, get fouled and
score."

The Sparks narrowed the deficit to 70-66 but Beard made a jumper
to extend the Mystics' advantage to 72-66 with 1:07 remaining. Los
Angeles failed to make a field goal in the final 4:36, scoring just
six points on free throws.
